    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.5.29" />
                
                <fw type="curatorial">29</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">LELAND STANFORD JUNIOR UNIVERSITY
                        <lb/>
                    DEPARTMENT OF ENGLISH</hi>
                        <lb/>
                
                    <hi rend="italics">Stanford University, California,</hi></fw>
                <opener><dateline>August 12, 1918</dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I am making a poetic anthology, designed especially for younger readers (say fourteen to twenty), which will be published sometime next year by Messrs. Scribner, and will include both the classics and the work of living writers. I should like to include some of your narrative verse, if it would be agreeable to you to do so, but am not sure--apart from the question of your wishes--whether it is practicable. "Epics," of course, cannot be reprinted entire, and yet it is the new epic spirit in which I am especially interested; there is lyric poetry enough and to spare, to choose from. I have had some thought of asking your leave to include the last section of "Hugh Glass," with a preliminary explanation of the story of the whole; I admire that conclusion very much. The best thing at present seems to me to ask your advice, in case you would like me to use anything of yours. Is it possible that the second poem, from which you read to us here, will be out soon, and that something in that would lend itself to selection better than anything in the former volume? Or have you <add>^published</add> any comparitively brief narrative poem which you would suggest for the purpose? I know that you will sympathize with my main purpose, which is to show that narrative poetry is still alive, and at work on themes near home. Any help you can offer will be warmly appreciated.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Cordially yours,</salute>
                    
                    <signed>Raymond M. Alden</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
